    <item>
      <title>On a special property of numbers of the form @n^k &#43; 1@</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/posts/blog-1/</link>
      <pubDate>Fri, 22 Nov 2024 02:27:08 +0530</pubDate>
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/posts/blog-1/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;In this blog post we would be looking at some bounds on largest prime factors of numbers of the form @n^k + 1@.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Let @k@ be a positive integer, and let @\epsilon@ be a positive real number. Prove that there are infinitely many positive integers @n@, such that the largest prime factor of @n^k + 1@ is less than @n^\epsilon@.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;In the whole solution @k@ and @ \epsilon @ is fixed.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
